Iv 38o—1 ...... sed gurgite puro vito redit, vr 140—1 quem rrou mille simul turmis uec Caesare toto auferret Fortuna locum [Manilius I 780 (os Manlius) et Ioue qui meruit caelum is sar harsher than these].

VII 798 iuue'eiet igru rogi miseris, Ix 424-5 (Libya) reon aere aeque auro excoquitur, are more familiar.

The attributive ablative, so common in Vergil, is rare in Lucan. Instances are IV 814 ciuem tauta indole, V 244-5 maesto classica paulurn intermissa sono, VII 155 immensoque igne co· lumuas.

The ablative absolute is sometimes strangely used, as in VIII 706-7 felt're retello turbante deoruru et nullo parcente ruiser, which might be called an attributive use.

Lucan prefers to use ob in many places where the plain ablative is more usual, as 11493 prolatus ab ira, VI 208 oppressus ab armis.
